WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.950 --> 00:00:11.790
Hi everyone, I'm Stefan from the Freewings flight school and today I'd like to tell you a bit about aerodynamics.

2
00:00:12.330 --> 00:00:16.150
Aerodynamics in general, but mainly paraglider-specific.

3
00:00:18.050 --> 00:00:22.730
The question that surely occupies all of us is why a paraglider flies at all.

4
00:00:23.150 --> 00:00:28.650
It hasn't let go of me since the first moment I saw a paraglider as a child.

5
00:00:28.650 --> 00:00:41.290
I'm always fascinated by why a paraglider made of fabric and a few lines, pulled out of a backpack, can lift us into the air and let us fly with it.

6
00:00:41.730 --> 00:00:50.760
If you get to the bottom of it, you quickly find that a paraglider works exactly the same way as any aeroplane, like any bird too.

7
00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:58.360
We have a wing that generates lift, which produces a force that keeps us in the air.

8
00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:12.450
I sometimes compare it with a car: you can drive any car, but whether you really understand how the clutch and engine and everything works isn't usually the decisive thing.

9
00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:22.380
With a paraglider too, you can be a super top pilot and not really know what's going on above you.

10
00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:27.300
But I'm convinced that, when paragliding, it's relatively important

11
00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:55.070
compared to car driving — that you also understand the technical background a bit, because it contributes to safety, and also, if you want to get the full performance out of the wing later when things get a bit more ambitious, having background knowledge about aerodynamics lets you get more out of your wing.

12
00:01:55.070 --> 00:01:57.970
It all started a very, very long time ago.

13
00:01:58.350 --> 00:01:59.070
Otto Lilienthal.

14
00:01:59.530 --> 00:02:12.570
He started experimenting in 1891 and built the first, you can almost say, hang gliders, and even carried out the first successful flights.

15
00:02:13.270 --> 00:02:23.060
He started early on observing birds and realised that not all birds need to flap their wings to stay in the air.

16
00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:29.560
He mainly looked at the larger birds and noticed that they can glide quite well without doing anything.

17
00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:45.410
And then he started taking storks apart, dissecting dead animals, and noticed that the wings of these animals all have a certain airfoil shape.

18
00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:59.410
He then began transferring that wing profile to his own wings and discovered that you can generate lift that carries you into the air after just a few running steps.

19
00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:09.730
In general, there are several attempts to explain, or reasons, why a wing flies.

20
00:03:09.730 --> 00:03:20.110
Basically there are three approaches, or three principles, why a wing generates lift and keeps us in the air.

21
00:03:20.110 --> 00:03:26.700
The first approach is Bernoulli's theory, and that has to do with fluid dynamics.

22
00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:33.700
You can see here we have an airfoil section that, like most airfoils, is asymmetric.

23
00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:37.700
That means there's more curvature on the top than on the bottom.

24
00:03:37.700 --> 00:03:49.020
This causes the air on top to have to circulate faster, to flow faster, and that creates lower pressure.

25
00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:52.020
On the underside of the wing, it's exactly the opposite.

26
00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:58.660
There the airflow is slower and higher pressure builds up.

27
00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:04.660
You can see the low-pressure and high-pressure regions are split into countless little forces.

28
00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:06.660
Those are small force vectors.

29
00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:13.660
If you bundle them all together and combine all the forces at one point, one resultant force emerges.

30
00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:21.710
That is the lift that allows us to fly, the force that acts upward.

31
00:04:21.710 --> 00:04:26.300
The split between them is a little tip for the theory exam.

32
00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:33.300
The split is two-thirds low pressure on the upper surface and one-third high pressure on the lower surface.

33
00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:35.300
It's a bit confusing wording-wise.

34
00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.300
You have to watch out not to mix things up here.

35
00:04:37.300 --> 00:04:44.900
At some point the flow stops following the profile and starts to separate back here.

36
00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:51.900
We call that the separation point — back here it creates small turbulence and somewhat chaotic air.

37
00:04:51.900 --> 00:04:54.900
We'll come back to that in detail later.

38
00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:56.900
So in essence, Bernoulli's theory:

39
00:04:56.900 --> 00:05:02.940
fluid dynamics, low pressure, high pressure — the first approach to why the wing flies.

40
00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:06.220
Then the second is the recoil principle.

41
00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:17.620
That's Newton's action equals reaction — he found out that on every body where some force acts, an opposing force is generated.

42
00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:23.620
Maybe you've tried it: when you stick your hand out of a moving car —

43
00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:30.620
perhaps not as the driver, perhaps as a passenger paying close attention to what exactly happens —

44
00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:32.620
if you hold your hand straight out,

45
00:05:32.620 --> 00:05:38.620
not much happens, you don't feel much drag, because the hand lies flat in the wind.

46
00:05:38.620 --> 00:05:44.620
But if you tilt your hand a little, in that direction, there's a force that pulls upward.

47
00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:48.620
And if you tilt it the other way, it pushes your hand downward instead.

48
00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:52.620
And the wing actually uses this recoil principle too,

49
00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:57.620
because the wing also has a certain angle to the oncoming air.

50
00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:00.620
We call that the angle of attack — we'll come back to it later.

51
00:06:00.620 --> 00:06:08.990
And this too generates a force that points upward and keeps us in the air.

52
00:06:08.990 --> 00:06:15.990
The third approach for why a wing generates lift is the so-called circulation flow.

53
00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:25.620
At the sharp trailing edge of the wing a starting vortex develops and that flow is deflected downward.

54
00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:30.620
And this in turn gives a moment or force upward,

55
00:06:30.620 --> 00:06:33.620
which also contributes to this dynamic lift.

56
00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:39.510
So those are the three approaches that keep the wing in the air.

57
00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:46.300
Now we come to a few technical terms regarding airfoils.

58
00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:50.300
We're still looking at the wing in cross-section for the moment.

59
00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:56.300
Later we'll look at the whole thing as a paraglider, the whole wing across the span,

60
00:06:56.300 --> 00:07:01.300
and the lines and the pilot hanging underneath, and what influence that has.

61
00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:04.300
For the moment we're just looking at the cross-section.

62
00:07:04.300 --> 00:07:08.860
And on paragliders the profile is relatively thick.

63
00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:11.860
You can see here, the profile thickness is the blue bar.

64
00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:17.940
It's relatively thick compared to, for example, a fast aircraft —

65
00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:24.940
a fighter jet, where the profile would be very flat, less asymmetric and rather thinner.

66
00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:30.940
So slow aircraft, which already produce a lot of lift at a low launch speed,

67
00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:38.300
without having to generate huge speed first,

68
00:07:38.300 --> 00:07:41.670
are designed to be rather thick and asymmetric.

69
00:07:41.670 --> 00:07:46.780
Chord length is essentially the distance from the front-most point to the rear-most point.

70
00:07:46.780 --> 00:07:50.780
On the paraglider, leading edge and trailing edge — terms you know,

71
00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:54.780
which you'll keep using again and again in flight practice.

72
00:07:54.780 --> 00:07:57.780
Chord line is more of a theoretical term.

73
00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:00.780
It's the straight line connecting the front-most and rear-most points.

74
00:08:01.780 --> 00:08:04.780
Not to be confused with the chord length.

75
00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:06.900
That's just the distance.

76
00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:09.900
And the chord line is really the line connecting those two points.

77
00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:14.480
Now we come to the forces and vectors.

78
00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:23.480
I mentioned briefly that there are multiple force vectors on a wing because of this lift.

79
00:08:23.480 --> 00:08:30.480
And these can all be summed up into one main vector, this lift vector.

80
00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:32.480
Later we'll also learn

81
00:08:32.480 --> 00:08:38.480
that this is the total aerodynamic force, composed of lift and drag.

82
00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:40.480
But more on that later.

83
00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:45.040
First, theoretically, how it looks with the vectors.

84
00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:48.040
This is a classic theory exam question.

85
00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:52.040
When you want to add forces together,

86
00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:58.040
or when two different forces act on a body at the same point of application,

87
00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:01.040
you can essentially chain these forces together.

88
00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:02.040
You see an example here.

89
00:09:03.040 --> 00:09:06.040
Forces F1 and F4 act on a body.

90
00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:08.040
They have the same point of application.

91
00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:12.040
What is the resultant R of the two forces?

92
00:09:12.040 --> 00:09:16.150
So on the left you have F1 and F4 that you'd have to pick out.

93
00:09:16.150 --> 00:09:21.650
Then you chain them together and see what the result is.

94
00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:27.650
If you take F4 and attach it from the end point of F1,

95
00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:32.700
and then connect the start point of both to the end point,

96
00:09:32.700 --> 00:09:36.700
we see the result is a diagonal force

97
00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:39.700
that has changed direction somewhat.

98
00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:41.700
That's the sum of the two forces.

99
00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:44.700
And in this example, that's R2.

100
00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:50.920
Then we have another example right after.

101
00:09:50.920 --> 00:09:53.920
If the forces act in the same direction,

102
00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:55.920
it's of course even simpler.

103
00:09:55.920 --> 00:09:57.920
Then there's no diagonal or anything,

104
00:09:57.920 --> 00:09:59.920
you can just add the forces together.

105
00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:02.920
In the exam, for example, you can count the squares here

106
00:10:02.920 --> 00:10:04.920
and you see F1 plus F2.

107
00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:05.920
Four squares plus two squares.

108
00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:10.610
Gives you the three — wait, six — squares of R3.

109
00:10:10.610 --> 00:10:13.610
But it can also be that the forces act in opposite directions.

110
00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:17.720
And let's assume the forces are exactly equal in magnitude:

111
00:10:17.720 --> 00:10:22.720
we have some stone here and a force pushes from each side.

112
00:10:22.720 --> 00:10:26.720
If they are exactly equal, the stone stays exactly in place.

113
00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:32.460
And here you see that F1, which is smaller,

114
00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:34.460
weakens F3 a bit.

115
00:10:34.460 --> 00:10:36.460
And again here, the sum:

116
00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:40.460
you can add the forces together and the sum is then R4.

117
00:10:40.460 --> 00:10:49.350
This basic knowledge is still important to understand the next few slides.

118
00:10:49.350 --> 00:10:53.350
Here we again have a wing, with the chord line drawn in.

119
00:10:53.350 --> 00:10:56.350
It's aerodynamically quite important.

120
00:10:56.350 --> 00:10:58.350
We'll see that in a moment.

121
00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:02.350
We have the total aerodynamic force I mentioned earlier.

122
00:11:02.350 --> 00:11:07.000
We have lift and drag.

123
00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
The absolute dream case would of course be

124
00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.000
to build a wing

125
00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
that generates no drag.

126
00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
No air resistance, that is.

127
00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
But that's simply not possible,

128
00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
because we have a certain frontal area,

129
00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
a certain surface that has to move against the air.

130
00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
And that always creates drag.

131
00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
However perfect a wing we build,

132
00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
we'd never get rid of that small drag force

133
00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:29.000
that acts against us.

134
00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
We could never get rid of it completely.

135
00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
And lift and drag combined,

136
00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.000
you can see here too,

137
00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
again form a triangle.

138
00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:38.000
And its diagonal

139
00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.560
is then the total aerodynamic force.

140
00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:43.560
Still important — shown on the left —

141
00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:45.670
lift and drag

142
00:11:45.670 --> 00:11:48.670
are always at a 90-degree angle to each other.

143
00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:49.670
They don't vary —

144
00:11:49.670 --> 00:11:51.670
they are always at exactly 90 degrees.

145
00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:56.690
Drag is always exactly in line with the airflow.

146
00:11:56.690 --> 00:12:01.150
So along the flight path, or along the airflow.

147
00:12:01.150 --> 00:12:03.150
It depends on how you look at it.

148
00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:05.150
It actually doesn't really matter

149
00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.150
whether the wing is in a wind tunnel,

150
00:12:07.150 --> 00:12:08.150
completely theoretically,

151
00:12:08.150 --> 00:12:11.150
or whether the wing glides through still air.

152
00:12:11.150 --> 00:12:13.150
Ultimately it's always relative,

153
00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:15.150
the wing against the air.

154
00:12:15.150 --> 00:12:20.620
The centre of pressure is also important —

155
00:12:20.620 --> 00:12:21.620
not to forget,

156
00:12:21.620 --> 00:12:22.620
the centre of pressure is the point

157
00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:25.620
where the sum of all these forces acts.

158
00:12:25.620 --> 00:12:27.620
And the weight force

159
00:12:27.620 --> 00:12:28.620
is always equal in magnitude

160
00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:31.620
to the total aerodynamic force.

161
00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:33.700
So if we're heavier,

162
00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:34.700
we need more lift

163
00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:35.700
and more drag,

164
00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:39.700
and the total aerodynamic force grows too.

165
00:12:39.700 --> 00:12:47.250
Then we go straight on with this slide

166
00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:49.250
about the inflow direction

167
00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:51.250
that I briefly mentioned earlier.

168
00:12:51.250 --> 00:12:52.250
The inflow direction,

169
00:12:52.250 --> 00:12:54.250
which runs in exactly the same direction

170
00:12:54.250 --> 00:12:55.250
as drag.

171
00:12:55.250 --> 00:12:58.250
And here we see the angle of attack.

172
00:12:58.250 --> 00:12:59.250
That's the hand again,

173
00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:01.250
which is somewhat at an angle,

174
00:13:01.250 --> 00:13:03.250
slightly tilted in this air channel

175
00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:06.250
or in this airflow.

176
00:13:06.250 --> 00:13:07.250
And the angle of attack —

177
00:13:07.250 --> 00:13:09.330
it's not the angle

178
00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:11.330
from the horizontal to the airflow,

179
00:13:11.330 --> 00:13:12.330
but always,

180
00:13:12.330 --> 00:13:13.330
very important,

181
00:13:13.330 --> 00:13:14.330
not to be confused —

182
00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:16.330
the angle of attack is always

183
00:13:16.330 --> 00:13:17.330
the angle of the wing,

184
00:13:17.330 --> 00:13:19.330
i.e. of the chord line,

185
00:13:19.330 --> 00:13:22.110
and the oncoming air.

186
00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:24.110
And the oncoming air

187
00:13:24.110 --> 00:13:26.110
is actually not horizontal,

188
00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:27.110
because with a paraglider

189
00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:29.110
you always have a slight sink.

190
00:13:29.110 --> 00:13:30.110
That's why here too it's

191
00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:32.110
drawn coming slightly from below,

192
00:13:32.110 --> 00:13:34.110
because you always sink slightly,

193
00:13:34.110 --> 00:13:37.260
if you simply look at neutral,

194
00:13:37.260 --> 00:13:44.590
unmoving, still air.

195
00:13:44.590 --> 00:13:45.590
Then we come to the drag

196
00:13:45.590 --> 00:13:47.700
of a body.

197
00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:50.010
What's interesting here:

198
00:13:50.010 --> 00:13:51.010
the formulas for drag

199
00:13:51.010 --> 00:13:52.010
and lift

200
00:13:52.010 --> 00:13:54.090
are always exactly the same.

201
00:13:54.090 --> 00:13:56.090
On the left there's W for drag (Widerstand),

202
00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:59.330
after that we have a few factors

203
00:13:59.330 --> 00:14:01.330
that complete the drag.

204
00:14:01.330 --> 00:14:03.330
Very important here —

205
00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:04.330
please don't be alarmed,

206
00:14:04.330 --> 00:14:06.330
for the theory exam,

207
00:14:06.330 --> 00:14:08.330
for the SHV theory exam,

208
00:14:08.330 --> 00:14:10.330
you don't have to memorise formulas

209
00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:13.330
or compute anything of this kind,

210
00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:14.330
so don't panic.

211
00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:16.330
I only drew the formulas

212
00:14:16.330 --> 00:14:17.330
to show you

213
00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:19.330
from which elements

214
00:14:19.330 --> 00:14:21.330
the drag is ultimately

215
00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:22.330
composed.

216
00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:24.980
First we have the coefficient,

217
00:14:24.980 --> 00:14:26.980
that's the shape and the angle of attack.

218
00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:28.980
It depends on

219
00:14:28.980 --> 00:14:29.980
whether it's a wing,

220
00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:30.980
or a car,

221
00:14:30.980 --> 00:14:31.980
or some stone in the wind.

222
00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:34.980
It depends a lot on the shape,

223
00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:37.980
how this device

224
00:14:37.980 --> 00:14:38.980
or this object

225
00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:40.980
is exposed to the wind stream.

226
00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:43.450
Then we have the air density,

227
00:14:43.450 --> 00:14:44.450
with this symbol,

228
00:14:44.450 --> 00:14:45.450
here written as rho.

229
00:14:45.450 --> 00:14:46.450
Air density is of course

230
00:14:46.450 --> 00:14:48.450
very important too.

231
00:14:48.450 --> 00:14:49.450
At sea level we don't have

232
00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:50.450
the same air density

233
00:14:50.450 --> 00:14:52.450
as up at 2,000 metres,

234
00:14:52.450 --> 00:14:53.450
which of course

235
00:14:53.450 --> 00:14:55.450
also influences the drag.

236
00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:58.140
Then we have the velocity.

237
00:14:58.140 --> 00:14:59.140
Careful — velocity

238
00:14:59.140 --> 00:15:01.140
is always squared.

239
00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:04.140
Its influence is squared.

240
00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:05.140
We'll come back to that shortly,

241
00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:07.140
what exactly that means

242
00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:09.900
for us with the paraglider.

243
00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:10.900
And S is the size,

244
00:15:10.900 --> 00:15:13.900
i.e. the surface area of the object.

245
00:15:13.900 --> 00:15:16.880
For lift it's exactly the same,

246
00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:19.880
only the coefficient changes there.

247
00:15:19.880 --> 00:15:20.880
The remaining factors

248
00:15:20.880 --> 00:15:22.880
are the same.

249
00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:24.880
Lift has a different coefficient

250
00:15:24.880 --> 00:15:27.760
and thus it influences

251
00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:29.760
the lift up front

252
00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:32.540
or the force that arises

253
00:15:32.540 --> 00:15:34.540
and then yields lift.

254
00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:38.730
In the SHV exam questions,

255
00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:39.730
a kind of example comes up

256
00:15:39.730 --> 00:15:40.730
again and again.

257
00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:42.730
What happens

258
00:15:42.730 --> 00:15:46.870
if we have a certain surface area?

259
00:15:46.870 --> 00:15:47.870
It causes a certain

260
00:15:47.870 --> 00:15:48.870
drag in the wind.

261
00:15:48.870 --> 00:15:49.870
What happens if we now

262
00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:52.870
double or halve the area?

263
00:15:52.870 --> 00:15:54.890
And there it's always relatively simple.

264
00:15:54.890 --> 00:15:55.890
It's always linear.

265
00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:56.890
So if you double

266
00:15:56.890 --> 00:15:58.890
an object's area,

267
00:15:58.890 --> 00:16:00.890
the drag doubles too.

268
00:16:00.890 --> 00:16:01.890
If you halve it,

269
00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:03.890
the drag is halved.

270
00:16:03.890 --> 00:16:05.890
If the air density halves,

271
00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:06.890
because you want to launch

272
00:16:06.890 --> 00:16:08.890
much, much higher up, for example,

273
00:16:08.890 --> 00:16:09.890
with the paraglider,

274
00:16:09.890 --> 00:16:12.420
then the drag also halves.

275
00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:15.010
A very, very big exclamation mark

276
00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:17.010
applies to velocity.

277
00:16:17.010 --> 00:16:19.010
When it comes to velocity,

278
00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:21.020
everything behaves squared.

279
00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:23.020
So if velocity doubles,

280
00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:25.020
all these forces quadruple.

281
00:16:25.020 --> 00:16:27.020
If velocity triples,

282
00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:29.020
all these forces increase ninefold.

283
00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:31.020
So with these questions you always need to make sure

284
00:16:31.020 --> 00:16:32.020
not to,

285
00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:34.020
make sure you don't make sloppy mistakes

286
00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:36.020
and just click through quickly,

287
00:16:36.020 --> 00:16:38.020
but look very carefully:

288
00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:40.020
is it about some other factor

289
00:16:40.020 --> 00:16:42.020
or is it about the velocity

290
00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:43.020
of this airflow.

291
00:16:43.020 --> 00:16:44.020
Very important

292
00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:46.520
not to fall for that.

293
00:16:46.520 --> 00:16:48.520
Here's exactly such an example.

294
00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:51.110
I won't read the whole question out,

295
00:16:51.110 --> 00:16:54.110
but if you have 30 km/h

296
00:16:54.110 --> 00:16:55.110
with the surface area

297
00:16:55.110 --> 00:16:57.110
in one case,

298
00:16:57.110 --> 00:16:59.110
and in the second case

299
00:16:59.110 --> 00:17:01.110
90 km/h,

300
00:17:01.110 --> 00:17:03.110
then that's a tripling

301
00:17:03.110 --> 00:17:05.110
of the wind speed

302
00:17:05.110 --> 00:17:07.110
and a ninefold increase

303
00:17:07.110 --> 00:17:09.110
of the drag.

304
00:17:09.110 --> 00:17:11.110
So 100 newtons doesn't become

305
00:17:11.110 --> 00:17:13.110
300 newtons, as you might guess,

306
00:17:13.110 --> 00:17:15.110
but 900.

307
00:17:15.110 --> 00:17:22.250
In our meteorology course

308
00:17:22.250 --> 00:17:24.250
you'll learn lots

309
00:17:24.250 --> 00:17:26.250
more important information

310
00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:28.250
about the atmosphere

311
00:17:28.250 --> 00:17:30.390
and the paraglider.

312
00:17:30.390 --> 00:17:32.390
With the paraglider

313
00:17:32.390 --> 00:17:34.390
it plays out this way:

314
00:17:34.390 --> 00:17:36.390
higher up

315
00:17:36.390 --> 00:17:38.440
we have less air density,

316
00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:40.440
there are fewer air particles,

317
00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:42.440
and our wing has to

318
00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:44.440
move faster through the air

319
00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:46.550
so it can generate the same lift.

320
00:17:46.550 --> 00:17:48.550
That means, very simply put,

321
00:17:48.550 --> 00:17:51.240
we need a higher launch speed.

322
00:17:51.240 --> 00:17:53.240
You can see on this curve

323
00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:55.240
that air pressure decreases with altitude.

324
00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:57.930
At 5,500 metres

325
00:17:57.930 --> 00:17:59.930
it's still

326
00:17:59.930 --> 00:18:01.930
only half as much,

327
00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:03.930
and along with air pressure

328
00:18:03.930 --> 00:18:05.930
air density also decreases,

329
00:18:05.930 --> 00:18:07.930
which appears in our formula.

330
00:18:07.930 --> 00:18:09.930
Air density only halves

331
00:18:09.930 --> 00:18:11.930
every 6,600 metres.

332
00:18:11.930 --> 00:18:13.930
Be careful not to mix them up.

333
00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:15.930
Watch out you don't confuse them.

334
00:18:15.930 --> 00:18:17.930
But ultimately it doesn't really matter

335
00:18:17.930 --> 00:18:19.930
whether it's 5,500

336
00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:21.930
or 6,500 —

337
00:18:21.930 --> 00:18:23.940
for the theory exam, of course it does,

338
00:18:23.940 --> 00:18:25.940
but in practice it has the same effect.

339
00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:27.940
The effect is

340
00:18:27.940 --> 00:18:29.940
that air density decreases,

341
00:18:29.940 --> 00:18:31.940
there are fewer air particles,

342
00:18:31.940 --> 00:18:33.940
and somehow we have to

343
00:18:33.940 --> 00:18:36.660
generate our lift,

344
00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:38.660
because the problem is —

345
00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:40.810
if you look at the formula —

346
00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:43.050
the drag coefficient stays the same,

347
00:18:43.050 --> 00:18:45.990
the surface area of our wing

348
00:18:45.990 --> 00:18:48.230
stays the same,

349
00:18:48.230 --> 00:18:50.230
our weight stays the same,

350
00:18:50.230 --> 00:18:52.230
meaning the lift we need to generate

351
00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:54.310
to get into the air,

352
00:18:54.310 --> 00:18:56.310
that stays the same, but our density

353
00:18:56.310 --> 00:18:58.310
is only half as much

354
00:18:58.310 --> 00:19:00.310
or smaller.

355
00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:02.310
That means up front, at A,

356
00:19:02.310 --> 00:19:04.310
at the lift, to land at the same value,

357
00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:06.310
we need to somehow compensate for that,

358
00:19:06.310 --> 00:19:08.310
and the only way:

359
00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:10.310
we have to do it through speed.

360
00:19:10.310 --> 00:19:12.310
It works in our favour, of course,

361
00:19:12.310 --> 00:19:14.310
that velocity is squared,

362
00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:16.310
which means at half air density

363
00:19:16.310 --> 00:19:18.310
we don't have to run twice as fast,

364
00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:20.310
only by

365
00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:22.310
the square root of 2.

366
00:19:22.310 --> 00:19:24.310
That's getting almost

367
00:19:24.310 --> 00:19:26.310
a bit too mathematical,

368
00:19:26.310 --> 00:19:28.310
what it means is, if you launch from a high mountain

369
00:19:28.310 --> 00:19:30.310
you need to be aware

370
00:19:30.310 --> 00:19:32.310
that you have to run much faster,

371
00:19:32.310 --> 00:19:34.310
which is usually a bit of a contradiction,

372
00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:36.310
because you're probably already tired,

373
00:19:36.310 --> 00:19:38.310
if maybe you hiked up,

374
00:19:38.310 --> 00:19:40.310
maybe you're standing in deep snow,

375
00:19:40.310 --> 00:19:42.310
maybe it drops off steeply in front,

376
00:19:42.310 --> 00:19:44.310
so simply keep in mind:

377
00:19:44.310 --> 00:19:46.310
we need more speed,

378
00:19:46.310 --> 00:19:49.030
more speed also means a longer running distance.

379
00:19:49.030 --> 00:19:51.030
On the other side, you shouldn't

380
00:19:51.030 --> 00:19:53.030
forget the advantages either.

381
00:19:53.030 --> 00:19:55.030
Up there it also tolerates

382
00:19:55.030 --> 00:19:57.030
a bit more wind, because the air

383
00:19:57.030 --> 00:19:59.030
thins out, so

384
00:19:59.030 --> 00:20:01.030
there are also advantages — maybe

385
00:20:01.030 --> 00:20:03.030
in a 30 km/h wind, as an experienced

386
00:20:03.030 --> 00:20:05.030
pilot, you can still launch where

387
00:20:05.030 --> 00:20:07.030
down at 1,500 metres

388
00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:09.030
with 30 it would already be pretty demanding

389
00:20:09.030 --> 00:20:11.030
and

390
00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:13.030
a launch would no longer be possible.

391
00:20:13.030 --> 00:20:18.440
Now we come back briefly

392
00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:20.440
to these drag coefficients,

393
00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:22.440
the Cd values.

394
00:20:22.440 --> 00:20:24.440
As I said, it really depends on

395
00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:26.440
what kind of object this is,

396
00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:28.440
whether it's a wing or something else.

397
00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:31.160
Important: when you

398
00:20:31.160 --> 00:20:34.460
compare objects,

399
00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:36.460
you should always start from the same

400
00:20:36.460 --> 00:20:38.460
frontal area.

401
00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:40.460
Now here, when you compare them,

402
00:20:40.460 --> 00:20:43.400
they all produce a certain

403
00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:45.400
drag when they're hit by air,

404
00:20:45.400 --> 00:20:47.400
but some produce much more

405
00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:49.400
than others. And that depends

406
00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:51.400
on the Cd value on the left.

407
00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:53.400
You can see, for example,

408
00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:55.400
the half-shell is 13 times,

409
00:20:55.400 --> 00:20:57.400
it produces 13 times more drag

410
00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:59.400
than that teardrop

411
00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:01.540
at the bottom of the list,

412
00:21:01.540 --> 00:21:03.540
which only has a Cd of 0.1.

413
00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:05.540
And here too there's

414
00:21:05.540 --> 00:21:07.590
occasionally

415
00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:10.090
a theory question:

416
00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:12.230
how many times smaller is

417
00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:14.230
a Cd value of 0.1

418
00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:16.230
compared to an object

419
00:21:16.230 --> 00:21:18.230
with a Cd value of 1.

420
00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:20.230
And the answer would be: ten times smaller.

421
00:21:23.510 --> 00:21:25.510
What I find interesting here

422
00:21:25.510 --> 00:21:27.800
is the comparison

423
00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:29.800
with nature.

424
00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:32.460
Nature always tends to seek

425
00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:34.460
the path of least resistance.

426
00:21:34.460 --> 00:21:36.460
Whether it's a lightning strike

427
00:21:36.460 --> 00:21:38.460
or a river winding through the landscape.

428
00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:40.460
It always goes

429
00:21:40.460 --> 00:21:42.460
with gravity and always

430
00:21:42.460 --> 00:21:44.460
where it's easiest.

431
00:21:44.460 --> 00:21:46.460
And if you look very closely,

432
00:21:46.460 --> 00:21:48.460
it actually looks like

433
00:21:48.460 --> 00:21:50.460
a raindrop. And a raindrop

434
00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:52.460
doesn't come down from the sky

435
00:21:52.460 --> 00:21:54.460
like a flat board, but

436
00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:56.460
comes down from the sky in such a way

437
00:21:56.460 --> 00:21:58.460
that it has the least drag possible and

438
00:21:58.460 --> 00:22:00.460
can fall as easily as possible to the ground.

439
00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:02.600
And this knowledge was

440
00:22:02.600 --> 00:22:04.600
put to use early on

441
00:22:04.600 --> 00:22:06.600
with these

442
00:22:06.600 --> 00:22:08.600
wind measurements. Namely with

443
00:22:08.600 --> 00:22:10.600
half-shells. If everything

444
00:22:10.600 --> 00:22:12.600
were spheres or all flat discs

445
00:22:12.600 --> 00:22:15.190
on such an anemometer,

446
00:22:15.190 --> 00:22:17.190
it wouldn't really move.

447
00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:19.190
Because then the force on all sides would be equal.

448
00:22:19.190 --> 00:22:21.190
But because they are half-shells,

449
00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:23.190
the wind that blows inside

450
00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:25.190
causes much

451
00:22:25.190 --> 00:22:27.190
more drag than the wind that blows on the outside.

452
00:22:27.190 --> 00:22:29.190
And that's why

453
00:22:29.190 --> 00:22:31.190
the wheel starts to turn.

454
00:22:31.190 --> 00:22:33.190
And that can be converted

455
00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:35.240
into a certain

456
00:22:35.240 --> 00:22:38.760
speed. Here too, the formula

457
00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:42.120
is shown below, which yields the drag.

458
00:22:42.120 --> 00:22:46.380
When we fly,

459
00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:48.380
we always have certain

460
00:22:48.380 --> 00:22:50.380
changes in angle of attack.

461
00:22:50.380 --> 00:22:52.380
Normally, if you simply let the wing

462
00:22:52.380 --> 00:22:54.380
fly, it flies at

463
00:22:54.380 --> 00:22:56.380
trim speed or at the

464
00:22:56.380 --> 00:22:58.380
angle of attack at which the wing

465
00:22:58.380 --> 00:23:00.380
is built. Or, depending on age,

466
00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:02.380
when it ages and the line lengths are no longer

467
00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:04.380
quite right, then the angle of attack

468
00:23:04.380 --> 00:23:06.380
may become a bit greater. But you can also

469
00:23:06.380 --> 00:23:08.380
influence it, for example by

470
00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:10.380
applying brake or accelerating.

471
00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:12.380
If you brake, the angle of attack

472
00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:14.380
increases because you pull the trailing edge

473
00:23:14.380 --> 00:23:16.380
down at the back, and the connection line

474
00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:18.380
then from the rear-most point

475
00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:20.380
to the front-most point

476
00:23:20.380 --> 00:23:22.380
naturally

477
00:23:22.380 --> 00:23:24.380
changes massively.

478
00:23:24.380 --> 00:23:26.380
And flight speed

479
00:23:26.380 --> 00:23:28.380
drops too, and thereby

480
00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:31.220
the angle of attack simply becomes larger.

481
00:23:31.220 --> 00:23:33.220
It looks roughly like this:

482
00:23:33.220 --> 00:23:35.220
the wing flies slower,

483
00:23:35.220 --> 00:23:37.220
Cd and Cl values

484
00:23:37.220 --> 00:23:39.220
increase. That's very important

485
00:23:39.220 --> 00:23:41.220
also for the theory exam, that you

486
00:23:41.220 --> 00:23:43.220
remember: when the angle of attack increases,

487
00:23:43.220 --> 00:23:45.240
the values increase.

488
00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:48.650
Conversely, when we

489
00:23:48.650 --> 00:23:50.650
accelerate the wing and

490
00:23:50.650 --> 00:23:52.650
the angle of attack decreases,

491
00:23:52.650 --> 00:23:54.650
then the Cd and Cl values

492
00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:57.460
decrease.

493
00:23:57.460 --> 00:23:59.460
Very important to know — we're actually always talking

494
00:23:59.460 --> 00:24:01.460
about steady gliding flight.

495
00:24:01.460 --> 00:24:03.460
Whether we're heavily braked

496
00:24:03.460 --> 00:24:05.460
or accelerated, it's always

497
00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:07.460
steady, and the wing

498
00:24:07.460 --> 00:24:09.460
flies on a line, in a stable

499
00:24:09.460 --> 00:24:11.460
state. And then, in

500
00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:13.460
steady gliding flight, the yellow arrow

501
00:24:13.460 --> 00:24:15.460
and the violet arrow — our force,

502
00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:17.460
our total aerodynamic force

503
00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:19.460
and weight force —

504
00:24:19.460 --> 00:24:21.580
are always equal.

505
00:24:21.580 --> 00:24:23.580
If we come out of full speed

506
00:24:23.580 --> 00:24:25.580
and brake, you know

507
00:24:25.580 --> 00:24:27.580
that the wing starts to climb,

508
00:24:27.580 --> 00:24:29.580
converting speed into altitude. In this phase

509
00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:31.580
our total aerodynamic force

510
00:24:31.580 --> 00:24:33.580
is briefly somewhat

511
00:24:33.580 --> 00:24:35.580
larger. Through this

512
00:24:35.580 --> 00:24:37.580
we generate lift and briefly gain

513
00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:39.580
altitude as well. But

514
00:24:39.580 --> 00:24:41.580
then it settles again

515
00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:43.580
and we're back in

516
00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:45.580
steady gliding flight. And then

517
00:24:45.580 --> 00:24:47.580
the two arrows, yellow and violet,

518
00:24:47.580 --> 00:24:49.580
are equal again and we fly

519
00:24:49.580 --> 00:24:53.800
stably and steadily.

520
00:24:53.800 --> 00:24:55.800
Then we come to the stagnation point.

521
00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:57.800
The stagnation point is the point on the wing

522
00:24:57.800 --> 00:24:59.800
where the air

523
00:24:59.800 --> 00:25:01.800
has to decide: do I go over the top

524
00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:03.800
or under the bottom.

525
00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:05.800
It's essentially the dividing point

526
00:25:05.800 --> 00:25:07.800
where the flow splits.

527
00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:09.800
And this point of course shifts,

528
00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:11.800
it doesn't stay in the same place,

529
00:25:11.800 --> 00:25:13.800
again to do with the angle of attack.

530
00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:16.490
You can see this point —

531
00:25:16.490 --> 00:25:18.700
if I increase

532
00:25:18.700 --> 00:25:20.840
the angle of attack here,

533
00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:22.840
this point migrates toward

534
00:25:22.840 --> 00:25:24.840
the trailing edge.

535
00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:26.840
And here you can also see why

536
00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:28.840
the cell openings on a paraglider

537
00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:30.920
are at the front

538
00:25:30.920 --> 00:25:32.920
on the underside, and not just

539
00:25:32.920 --> 00:25:34.920
straight ahead or on top.

540
00:25:34.920 --> 00:25:36.970
Because in this range, where we

541
00:25:36.970 --> 00:25:39.020
actually fly, we have our

542
00:25:39.020 --> 00:25:41.450
stagnation point pretty much

543
00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:43.450
exactly in this area, which is also

544
00:25:43.450 --> 00:25:45.450
where the cell openings are — which makes total sense.

545
00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:48.260
The separation point behaves

546
00:25:48.260 --> 00:25:50.260
in exactly the opposite way:

547
00:25:50.260 --> 00:25:52.260
when you brake more, the

548
00:25:52.260 --> 00:25:54.260
separation point — where the flow

549
00:25:54.260 --> 00:25:56.260
can no longer follow the profile — migrates further

550
00:25:56.260 --> 00:25:58.260
toward the leading edge.

551
00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:00.260
Until at some point the flow

552
00:26:00.260 --> 00:26:02.260
up here separates completely,

553
00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:04.260
the wing no longer generates lift,

554
00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:06.260
deflates,

555
00:26:06.260 --> 00:26:08.260
and we're in a full stall.

556
00:26:08.260 --> 00:26:12.070
Right, that's pretty much

557
00:26:12.070 --> 00:26:14.070
what happens with the stagnation point and the

558
00:26:14.070 --> 00:26:16.150
separation point when we change our

559
00:26:16.150 --> 00:26:18.150
angle of attack and brake

560
00:26:18.150 --> 00:26:21.510
hard. Then we come

561
00:26:21.510 --> 00:26:23.530
to the wingtip vortex and

562
00:26:23.530 --> 00:26:25.530
to drag. We've talked a lot

563
00:26:25.530 --> 00:26:27.530
about drag — now let's look at

564
00:26:27.530 --> 00:26:29.530
the whole system and how drag

565
00:26:29.530 --> 00:26:31.530
is roughly distributed on the paraglider,

566
00:26:31.530 --> 00:26:34.020
on the flying system.

567
00:26:34.020 --> 00:26:36.020
Profile drag, as you can see here,

568
00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:38.020
is about 20%.

569
00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:40.230
The lines are about 20%,

570
00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:42.230
the pilot is about

571
00:26:42.230 --> 00:26:44.230
20%, and the biggest

572
00:26:44.230 --> 00:26:46.230
part, which is somewhat

573
00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:48.230
hard to picture because it's the part

574
00:26:48.230 --> 00:26:50.230
the eye doesn't see,

575
00:26:50.230 --> 00:26:52.230
is induced drag.

576
00:26:52.230 --> 00:26:54.230
And induced drag is produced

577
00:26:54.230 --> 00:26:56.230
at the wingtip, because

578
00:26:56.230 --> 00:26:58.410
we have the high pressure

579
00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:01.030
and the low pressure, and these

580
00:27:01.030 --> 00:27:03.050
pressure differences want to

581
00:27:03.050 --> 00:27:05.050
equalise somehow.

582
00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:07.050
Such an imbalance is

583
00:27:07.050 --> 00:27:09.050
never good in nature

584
00:27:09.050 --> 00:27:11.050
or in physics — it always wants

585
00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:13.050
to balance itself out, and that produces

586
00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:15.190
the vortex at the wingtip,

587
00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:17.190
which can be quite strong

588
00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:19.190
in some cases — so if

589
00:27:19.190 --> 00:27:21.190
you fly very close behind another

590
00:27:21.190 --> 00:27:23.190
paraglider, you'll notice

591
00:27:23.190 --> 00:27:25.190
how it can shake you a bit.

592
00:27:25.190 --> 00:27:27.190
On landing, definitely not

593
00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:29.190
recommended to fly close together,

594
00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:31.190
better to keep some distance.

595
00:27:31.190 --> 00:27:33.190
The heavier the aircraft,

596
00:27:33.190 --> 00:27:35.190
whether it's a paraglider or

597
00:27:35.190 --> 00:27:37.190
a jumbo jet,

598
00:27:37.190 --> 00:27:39.240
the stronger the wingtip vortices.

599
00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:41.800
That means if you're flying behind

600
00:27:41.800 --> 00:27:43.800
a tandem during landing,

601
00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:45.800
you have to be very careful,

602
00:27:45.800 --> 00:27:47.800
because the vortices there

603
00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:49.800
are noticeably bigger than with

604
00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:53.370
a solo wing.

605
00:27:53.370 --> 00:27:55.370
Our goal — we said at the start —

606
00:27:55.370 --> 00:27:57.370
the ideal case would actually be that we

607
00:27:57.370 --> 00:27:59.370
have no drag at all and only lift.

608
00:27:59.370 --> 00:28:01.370
How do we get a bit

609
00:28:01.370 --> 00:28:03.370
closer to that? With the profile

610
00:28:03.370 --> 00:28:05.370
we can get some gains,

611
00:28:05.370 --> 00:28:07.450
because

612
00:28:07.450 --> 00:28:09.450
if you look at the wing,

613
00:28:09.450 --> 00:28:11.450
it has lots of

614
00:28:11.450 --> 00:28:13.450
waves and bumps because of the cells, which

615
00:28:13.450 --> 00:28:15.450
actually — if you look at aeroplanes,

616
00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:17.450
where the surface is nice and smooth — is

617
00:28:17.450 --> 00:28:19.450
actually inefficient and not so favourable.

618
00:28:19.450 --> 00:28:22.140
That's why on high-performance wings

619
00:28:22.140 --> 00:28:24.140
or intermediate wings,

620
00:28:24.140 --> 00:28:26.140
the further you go up the difficulty class,

621
00:28:26.140 --> 00:28:28.140
the more cells

622
00:28:28.140 --> 00:28:30.140
these wings have. And these cells make

623
00:28:30.140 --> 00:28:32.140
the waves

624
00:28:32.140 --> 00:28:34.140
as

625
00:28:34.140 --> 00:28:36.310
flat as possible — better

626
00:28:36.310 --> 00:28:38.310
many tiny waves than

627
00:28:38.310 --> 00:28:40.420
big humps. That gets you

628
00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:42.420
much closer to the desired

629
00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:45.140
ideal profile. But it requires

630
00:28:45.140 --> 00:28:47.140
that you can still control the device,

631
00:28:47.140 --> 00:28:49.140
because it just becomes much harder

632
00:28:49.140 --> 00:28:51.140
to fly. Induced drag

633
00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:53.140
is reduced via aspect ratio.

634
00:28:53.140 --> 00:28:55.140
On aeroplanes there are also

635
00:28:55.140 --> 00:28:57.140
those winglets you see,

636
00:28:57.140 --> 00:28:59.140
which go up at the wingtip,

637
00:28:59.140 --> 00:29:01.140
to reduce that vortex.

638
00:29:01.140 --> 00:29:03.140
On the paraglider you mainly tackle it

639
00:29:03.140 --> 00:29:05.140
through aspect ratio.

640
00:29:05.140 --> 00:29:07.140
We'll come back to aspect ratio

641
00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:09.140
later — it's basically

642
00:29:09.140 --> 00:29:11.140
a wider span and

643
00:29:11.140 --> 00:29:13.140
a smaller chord. So,

644
00:29:13.140 --> 00:29:15.140
the more the paraglider looks like a

645
00:29:15.140 --> 00:29:17.140
sickle in the sky and looks nice

646
00:29:17.140 --> 00:29:19.140
and slender, the more

647
00:29:19.140 --> 00:29:21.140
optimised the induced drag is.

648
00:29:21.140 --> 00:29:23.740
Next are the lines.

649
00:29:23.740 --> 00:29:25.740
Here ideally you want

650
00:29:25.740 --> 00:29:27.740
as few and as

651
00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:29.980
thin lines as possible.

652
00:29:29.980 --> 00:29:31.980
That also brings with it

653
00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:33.980
more knots, that it's

654
00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:35.980
more demanding to fly in case of

655
00:29:35.980 --> 00:29:38.060
a disturbance, and so on.

656
00:29:38.060 --> 00:29:40.060
So you see, all these factors

657
00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:42.710
actually mean

658
00:29:42.710 --> 00:29:44.710
that the wing becomes harder to fly

659
00:29:44.710 --> 00:29:46.710
and requires much more skill.

660
00:29:46.710 --> 00:29:49.400
And last but not least,

661
00:29:49.400 --> 00:29:51.450
the pilot

662
00:29:51.450 --> 00:29:53.450
also makes a big difference, of course —

663
00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:55.450
whether we sit upright inside

664
00:29:55.450 --> 00:29:57.450
and present a large area

665
00:29:57.450 --> 00:29:59.450
to the wind, or whether we

666
00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:01.450
lie thin and as small as possible.

667
00:30:01.450 --> 00:30:03.450
That again accounts for

668
00:30:03.450 --> 00:30:05.450
a few percent we can

669
00:30:05.450 --> 00:30:07.530
optimise. Here, quickly

670
00:30:07.530 --> 00:30:09.530
sketched, is roughly how a prone harness

671
00:30:09.530 --> 00:30:11.530
would look in the wind tunnel.

672
00:30:11.530 --> 00:30:13.530
So here too you see, in front

673
00:30:13.530 --> 00:30:15.530
as rounded as possible, so that

674
00:30:15.530 --> 00:30:17.530
the air that has hit it

675
00:30:17.530 --> 00:30:19.530
flows around

676
00:30:19.530 --> 00:30:21.530
nicely, like a raindrop.

677
00:30:21.530 --> 00:30:23.530
Then it flows nicely behind.

678
00:30:23.530 --> 00:30:26.180
Ideally

679
00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:28.330
the harness behind

680
00:30:28.330 --> 00:30:30.330
tapers into a point

681
00:30:30.330 --> 00:30:32.330
and is not suddenly sharp-edged,

682
00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:34.330
where the flow separates, but

683
00:30:34.330 --> 00:30:36.330
really runs into a slit

684
00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:38.330
or to a point at the back

685
00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:40.410
and then comes back together behind,

686
00:30:40.410 --> 00:30:42.410
so that as little

687
00:30:42.410 --> 00:30:44.410
turbulence as possible occurs back there.

688
00:30:44.410 --> 00:30:46.410
And that's how here too

689
00:30:46.410 --> 00:30:48.410
you can get the maximum.

690
00:30:48.410 --> 00:30:50.410
So the foot bag is not just

691
00:30:50.410 --> 00:30:52.410
to be nice and comfortable and warm,

692
00:30:52.410 --> 00:30:54.410
it's really also

693
00:30:54.410 --> 00:30:56.410
aerodynamically a fairly big

694
00:30:56.410 --> 00:30:59.000
difference, but again

695
00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.780
more demanding to fly.

696
00:31:01.780 --> 00:31:03.830
Now we come to the terminology.

697
00:31:03.830 --> 00:31:05.830
First we talk

698
00:31:05.830 --> 00:31:07.830
about wing span,

699
00:31:07.830 --> 00:31:09.830
and it's important to know that

700
00:31:09.830 --> 00:31:12.380
all these

701
00:31:12.380 --> 00:31:14.380
measurements we're

702
00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:16.380
talking about, on a paraglider

703
00:31:16.380 --> 00:31:18.380
always come in flat and projected.

704
00:31:18.380 --> 00:31:20.380
Because laid out flat, a

705
00:31:20.380 --> 00:31:22.380
wing is much bigger than

706
00:31:22.380 --> 00:31:24.380
when it's in the air.

707
00:31:24.380 --> 00:31:26.380
So the outermost two points

708
00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:28.380
measured in the air are a bit smaller

709
00:31:28.380 --> 00:31:30.380
than when the wing lies flat on the ground.

710
00:31:30.380 --> 00:31:32.380
And what's ultimately aerodynamically

711
00:31:32.380 --> 00:31:34.380
interesting, this area

712
00:31:34.380 --> 00:31:36.580
that we have in the air above our heads

713
00:31:36.580 --> 00:31:38.580
measured there, that generates

714
00:31:38.580 --> 00:31:40.580
lift, is always the projected

715
00:31:40.580 --> 00:31:42.760
area. But you

716
00:31:42.760 --> 00:31:44.760
sometimes have to watch out

717
00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:46.760
to make sure you're talking about the same thing, when

718
00:31:46.760 --> 00:31:48.760
someone says, oh you've got the 20 m²

719
00:31:48.760 --> 00:31:50.760
and the other

720
00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:52.760
says no, the 18 — if it's not

721
00:31:52.760 --> 00:31:54.760
the same measurement being discussed,

722
00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:56.810
then in some cases

723
00:31:56.810 --> 00:31:58.810
it can actually be the same paraglider.

724
00:31:58.810 --> 00:32:01.370
Because one is talking about flat (laid-out)

725
00:32:01.370 --> 00:32:03.370
span or area and the other

726
00:32:03.370 --> 00:32:05.370
is talking about projected.

727
00:32:05.370 --> 00:32:07.370
Then here we're at chord length.

728
00:32:07.370 --> 00:32:09.700
Here we actually always talk about

729
00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:11.700
the mean chord, because

730
00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:13.700
the chord at the stabilo here

731
00:32:13.700 --> 00:32:15.700
is much smaller

732
00:32:15.700 --> 00:32:17.700
than in the middle, and that's why

733
00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.700
an average is computed

734
00:32:19.700 --> 00:32:21.700
and then we actually speak of this

735
00:32:21.700 --> 00:32:24.650
mean chord.

736
00:32:24.650 --> 00:32:26.650
It's the chord that

737
00:32:26.650 --> 00:32:28.650
ultimately makes a wing more efficient,

738
00:32:28.650 --> 00:32:30.650
because as we've seen,

739
00:32:30.650 --> 00:32:32.650
induced drag is the

740
00:32:32.650 --> 00:32:34.650
largest drag, and with aspect ratio

741
00:32:34.650 --> 00:32:36.650
you can bring it down a bit.

742
00:32:36.650 --> 00:32:39.370
That's the ratio of span

743
00:32:39.370 --> 00:32:41.450
to mean chord.

744
00:32:41.450 --> 00:32:43.560
The mean chord can't simply

745
00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:45.560
be measured out — it's

746
00:32:45.560 --> 00:32:47.560
a value given by the manufacturer.

747
00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:49.560
You can, if you

748
00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:51.560
look at the fraction here — on top

749
00:32:51.560 --> 00:32:53.560
span divided by

750
00:32:53.560 --> 00:32:55.560
mean chord —

751
00:32:55.560 --> 00:32:58.220
you can also expand the fraction

752
00:32:58.220 --> 00:33:00.220
with span on top,

753
00:33:00.220 --> 00:33:02.220
span on the bottom too, and then

754
00:33:02.220 --> 00:33:04.220
at the bottom you get span

755
00:33:04.220 --> 00:33:06.220
squared divided by area.

756
00:33:06.220 --> 00:33:08.220
So either span

757
00:33:08.220 --> 00:33:10.220
divided by mean chord

758
00:33:10.220 --> 00:33:12.220
or span

759
00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:14.220
squared divided by area.

760
00:33:14.220 --> 00:33:16.220
That gives the same value

761
00:33:16.220 --> 00:33:18.220
under the line, and that's your

762
00:33:18.220 --> 00:33:23.300
aspect ratio of the wing.

763
00:33:23.300 --> 00:33:25.300
Here briefly the explanation again —

764
00:33:25.300 --> 00:33:27.350
projected area is,

765
00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:29.350
exaggerated, like if

766
00:33:29.350 --> 00:33:31.350
someone shone a torch on it

767
00:33:31.350 --> 00:33:33.350
or, even better, the sun shone on it,

768
00:33:33.350 --> 00:33:35.350
which is of course much further away —

769
00:33:35.350 --> 00:33:37.350
if you're right by the landing field

770
00:33:37.350 --> 00:33:39.350
or, say, near a windsock, where you could

771
00:33:39.350 --> 00:33:41.350
look and see how big the shadow is.

772
00:33:41.350 --> 00:33:43.350
That would roughly be the projected

773
00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:45.350
area, just to explain it.
